6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 635, L.D. 1551, “An Act to Support
10 Maine Eating and Drinking Establishments by Allowing Vendors to Operate on the
11 Premises of an Establishment with a Liquor License”
12 Amend the bill by inserting after the title and before the enacting clause the following:
13 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
14 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
15 Whereas, this legislation is a way to support Maine's hospitality sector and businesses
16 that cater to tourists, and the tourism season is crucial for the State's economy and public
17 well-being; and
18 Whereas, the tourism season, which brings millions of visitors and significant
19 revenue to the State, relies on a regulated and enjoyable environment, including accessible
20 and responsible alcohol sales; and
21 Whereas, for these reasons, this legislation needs to take effect before the expiration
22 of the 90-day period; and
23 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
24 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
25 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
26 therefore,'
27 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
28 following:
29 'Sec. 1. 28-A MRSA §1051-A is enacted to read:
30 §1051-A. Vendor operation on premises of host licensee
31 1. Definitions. For purposes of this section, unless the context otherwise indicates,
32 the following terms have the following meanings.
33 A. "Host licensee" means an establishment licensed under this chapter to sell liquor
34 for consumption on the premises and licensed by the Department of Health and Human
Page 1 - 132LR1467(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 635, L.D. 1551
315 Services or the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry to prepare, serve,
326 sell or offer for sale food that uses the services of a licensed vendor or unlicensed
337 vendor.
4 B. "Licensed vendor" means a person that holds a license issued by the Department of
5 Health and Human Services or the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and
6 Forestry to prepare, serve, sell or offer for sale food.
7 C. "Unlicensed vendor" means a person that does not hold a license issued by the
8 Department of Health and Human Services or the Department of Agriculture,
9 Conservation and Forestry to prepare, serve, sell or offer for sale food.
10 D. "Vendor" means a licensed vendor or unlicensed vendor.
11 2. Conditions. A vendor may operate on the premises of a host licensee under the
12 following conditions.
13 A. If an unlicensed vendor prepares, serves, sells or offers for sale any food on the
14 premises of a host licensee, the host licensee is responsible for ensuring that the
15 preparation, serving, selling or offering for sale of food complies with applicable food,
16 health and safety rules.
17 B. If a licensed vendor prepares, serves, sells or offers for sale food, the licensed
18 vendor is responsible for ensuring that its operations comply with food, health and
19 safety rules applicable to the license to prepare, serve, sell or offer for sale food as
20 issued by the Department of Health and Human Services or the Department of
21 Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry.
22 C. A vendor may serve alcoholic beverages on the premises of the host licensee only
23 if those beverages are supplied exclusively by the host licensee and the host licensee
24 or an employee of the host licensee who is authorized to serve liquor is present.
25 D. A vendor employee may serve alcohol only if the employee is authorized to serve
26 liquor and the vendor employee has provided to the host licensee an affidavit stating
27 that the vendor employee has not been convicted of a first offense of violating section
28 2078 or section 2081, subsection 1, paragraph A or B within 2 years of the date of the
29 affidavit nor convicted of a second offense of violating section 2078 or section 2081,
30 subsection 1, paragraph A or B within 5 years of the date of the affidavit. The affidavit
31 must be executed prior to the vendor operating on the premises of a host licensee. The
32 bureau shall develop the affidavit form required by this paragraph and provide a copy
33 of the affidavit to vendors.
34 E. A vendor employee who serves alcohol on the premises of the host licensee is
35 considered a server of the host licensee for purposes of the Maine Liquor Liability Act.
36 F. The host licensee must maintain for a period of at least one year a written record of
37 all operations involving vendors, including the name and contact information of the
38 vendor, menus offered by the vendor and the dates and times of operation.
39 G. The vendor is responsible for collecting and remitting all applicable state and federal
40 sales taxes on food and beverage sales conducted during its operations on the premises
41 of the host licensee.
42 H. A host licensee is liable for any violation of the liquor laws or any rule adopted by
43 the bureau committed by a vendor on the premises of the host licensee and is subject
Page 2 - 132LR1467(02)
